ce>ES/G009694/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The last four decades have witnessed the pluralisation of domestic security within Britain.&amp;nbsp; There has been a shift from a state-centred 'monopoly' model to a 'networked' model in which a multiplicity of both state and non-state institutions are actively engaged in policing functions.&amp;nbsp; Consequently, there are now twice as many private security guards as there are police officers patrolling the streets and businesses of Britain today.&amp;nbsp; In 2003, a new non-departmental public body called the Security Industry Authority (SIA) was formed to regulate the industry and ensure that these private security guards operated in accordance with 'good' policing practices.&amp;nbsp; The SIA has therefore come to assume a critical role in balancing the demand for private security with the widespread expectation that domestic security ought to be delivered as a non-rival, non-excludable public good.&amp;nbsp; The objective of this project is to evaluate the effectiveness of the SIA in accomplishing this delicate balance.&amp;nbsp; This will be achieved in two ways: first, by surveying and interviewing elites within the SIA, the Home Office and ACPO to get the view from the centre; and second, by conducting four city-based case studies (in London, Sheffield, Cardiff and Edinburgh) to obtain the view from the ground.
